USERS GROUPS - PERMISSION
-------------------------
Linux is the multiple user system - Each user has control access

To manage this , Linux has
. Users
. Group
. Premission

USERS?
A user is an identity that can:
. Log into the system
. Own files
. Run commands

Types of users
Type            Desc 
Root user       Super Admin (full access)
Normal user     Limited access
System user     Used by services (like nginx)

Commands

# Create user
sudo adduser <User_name>

# Switch user
su <user-name>

# Check current user
whoami

GROUPS?
A group is a collection of users
. Manage permissions easily
. Give access to multiple users

Commands

# Create group 
sudo groupadd <developers>

# Add user to group
sudo usermod -aG <developers> <user_name>

# Check groups
groups <user_name>

# Command to check list of users in a Group
grep <group_name> /etc/group


PERMISSIONS?
Every file has 3 permissions

|Symbol    |    Meaning |
|----------|------------|
|r         |    read    |
|w         |    write   |
|x         |    execute |
|----------|------------|

d => directory 
- => file

Permission Structure
-rwxr-xr--

First represents file/directory
Next groups as 333
First 3 (rwx)  - Owner (file creator) permision
Second 3 (r-x) - Group (assigned group) permission
Third 3 (r--)  - Others(everyone else) 

# Change Permission
chmod 

* Numeric method
 Permissions : read = 4 , write = 2 , execute = 1
 Numbers       Permissions 
 --------------------------
 7               rwx
 6               rw-
 5               r-x
 4               r--

example : chmod 755 file.txt (-rwxr-xr-x)

* Symbolic method
 chmod +x file.txt

 Other variations
 Only Owner : chmod u+x file.sh
 Only Group : chmod g+x file.sh
 Only other : chmod o+x file.sh
 Multiple   : chmod ug+x file.sh

 # Check the ownership
 ls -l

 